𝗪𝗵𝘆 𝗶𝘀 𝗶𝘁 𝗶𝗺𝗽𝗼𝗿𝘁𝗮𝗻𝘁 𝘁𝗼 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗺𝗼𝗿𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗮𝗻 𝗷𝘂𝘀𝘁 𝗽𝗵𝘆𝘀𝗶𝗾𝘂𝗲 𝗯𝗮𝘀𝗲𝗱 𝗴𝗼𝗮𝗹𝘀? 🍑

If we purely focus on the number on the scale, or the way we look in the mirror, we will miss so many accomplishments and victories we achieve along the way. Every day will be a luck of the draw, because our bodies fluctuate on a daily/ weekly basis, and this may have nothing to do with the effort we’re putting into our training or nutrition, it’s just the joys of being a human! 👏🏼

This means, that if we were to purely focus on the way we look, we would get disappointed quite regally, and feel like we’re not progressing when you really are- You may just holding onto more fluid because you’re hormonal, you had more sodium the day before, you didn’t get enough sleep, you’re dehydrated, you’re stressed, you had a food that irritates your gut, you didn’t go to the toilet, & the list goes on. 

Not only this, but physique based goals can get very negative, and never seem to be enough, even when you reach your supposed ‘goal weight’, we always want more & better. You may also have the goal to look like someone you see on instagram, but your genetics are completely different, which makes it extremely challenging to achieve that goal, and can leave you feeling really disheartened. 
Genetics do play a role in body composition, if you and I did the exact same workouts and ate the exact same meals, we would all still look completely different, so it’s important to always aim to be the best version of YOU, rather then trying to be exactly like someone else. 

I’m not saying you shouldn’t have a physique based goal, not at all. It’s so important to have a goal in mind and something you want to work towards, but you should have so many other goals along side this; Strength based gaols, nutrition goals, consistency goals, mindset goals. Give yourself a chance to be proud more regularly, focus on the things you can control daily, knowing that your daily habits will naturally lead to the end result. 
By focussing on other areas you can control, you’ll be happy and proud every step of the way to achieving your goal, not just when you reach it. 🦋💛

As this year comes to an end, take a moment to be proud of yourself. 

Proud of the things you overcome that felt earth shattering at the time, proud of the lessons you learnt that have made you stronger and wiser, proud of your resilience, effort, and determination to keep showing up for yourself, to keep trying no matter how hard it was.

As so many show all the highlight reels of this year, it’s easy to get caught up in maybe how ‘not so great’ this year may have been for you, but I want to remind you that making it through the year is something amazing, something to never take for granted.

This chapter may not have been the brightest for you, but I promise it’s a necessary part of your story. My lowest points have always led me to my highest, they are the parts that help build you up to become the person you’re meant to be. Sometimes when things seem to be falling apart, they may actually be falling into place. 🦋

I hope 2023 brings you all an immense amount of happiness, success, love, and fulfilment. Follow your dreams, take that risk, stay true to yourself, listen to your gut, and do more of the things that make you feel good. 
Sending you all so much love, happy NYE 🤍✨
Grateful for the year that was, excited for the year ahead. 🥰🫶🏼

𝗕𝘆 𝗯𝗶𝗴𝗴𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝘁𝗶𝗽𝘀 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝗡𝗲𝘄 𝗬𝗲𝗮𝗿𝘀 𝗴𝗼𝗮𝗹𝘀 ✨

1. Start your goals smaller- don’t set big unrealistic expectations on yourself that you know you will really struggle to stick to. Less a lot of the time is better, focus on healthy sustainable changes, show yourself you CAN do it, and then build from there as it becomes easier and continue to level up your goals. 📈
2. Motivation will eventually run out, focus on building habits and routines that align with what it is you want to achieve. Motivation will get you started, but discipline is what keeps you going. Consistency is KEY. 🔑
3. A goal without a plan is just a wish. If you’re trying to build new habits, or accomplish anything you you need to have a plan, a daily routine. Your daily habits are what LEAD to the end result- good or bad. Try to be as consistent as possible with the time you wake up, go to bed, train, eat, walk, meditate. Taking it a step further- having a training plan, meal plan, a coach to support and educate you, (or whatever your goal is!), morning and night routines that prime you for your day. Failing to prepare is preparing to fail. 🎯
4. Patience. You need to be in it for the long haul, otherwise you’ll reach your goal just to end up exactly where you are now. Take your time to build the habits, ensure the approach is sustainable and something you enjoy, get assistance if needed, and be consistent. If you want 2023 to be different, YOU need to be different. 🙏🏼

The person you want to become, the goals you want to achieve, you need to live NOW as that person. You need to show up, you need to be honest with yourself in what’s holding you back and what action you need to take. Will it be hard? Yeah, I’m sure it will be at times. But you need to choose your hard. Staying exactly where you are and never progressing towards your dreams, or getting uncomfortable at times to live an extraordinary life. 🦋🌈🤍

Morning in the life 🫶🏼✨

PLEASE read the caption 💛

Win the morning, win the day ☀️🦋
I have small things I implement into my day that help me ground and connect to myself. I’m a huge advocate for waking up earlier and investing time into yourself before getting stuck in the busyness of life, work and other commitments. 📝🌅

I have a solid 2 hours of me time before the day begins. Time I get to spend doing things that make me feel at peace, grateful, happy. Time I pour into myself before pouring into others. This is where I set the tone for my day and make myself and the quality of my life a priority. 💫

You can’t give the world the best of you without putting in the time and effort to look after yourself first- inside and out. 
Even 10 minutes of self care is better than nothing. Slow down, check in with yourself, do something that makes you feel happy and at peace, find something to be grateful for each and every single morning. 🍀

**A big non-negotiable habit I have is to not touch social media of any kind in these first few hours. The key is to be present, set your intentions and feed your mind with positive and empowering things that will flow into your day. If we instantly turn to social media we let this control how we feel, and start our day by being disconnected, unsettled, and giving away our power. 🚫📱**

I used to live my life hating my body, wanting to change ‘this’ or ‘that’, thinking that achieving a certain body fat would mean I’d be confident and happy within myself.. 

I promise you now, from lived experience that a negative relationship towards yourself and your body will only get you further away from that, it will only magnify what you don’t like, what you want to change, even when you’ve reached your supposed ‘goal’. 
The acceptance, love and validation you seek must come from yourself. & I promise once you learn this you will thrive. 💗

The best results I’ve achieved have come from a place of love for myself- from training to feel more empowered, stronger, healthier, because I genuinely enjoy it and it makes me feel good- not because I feel like I need to punish myself & burn calories. From fueling my body to nourish it and support it in everything it does to keep me alive on a daily basis- not deprive and starve myself. 

It’s cool to look good, but I promise it’s cooler to feel good. 💫

𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝘄𝗼𝗿𝗸𝗼𝘂𝘁 + 𝗰𝘂𝗲𝘀:
A. BB Good-morning 12/10/8 reps 
*Feet just outside hip width, tight upper back & braced core, screw feet into the ground, bend knees, push hips back & focus on stretching through glutes & hamstrings allowing chest to lower whilst keeping neutral spine. initiate through glutes & come back to starting position.

B. Dead stop BB Hip thrust + 10 sec hold on last rep 🥲 3x 10 
*use decline bench- chin tucked, knees in 90° angle at top position, push down through heels, drive up through glutes while keeping core braced, pause at the top & squeeze glutes as hard as you can.

C. Lying hamstring curl 3x 12 
*screw hips into the pad, focus on squeezing up through hamstrings rather than just bringing the weight up & using momentum.

D. Cable step up -glute focussed 3x 10ea 
*keep shin vertical, drive non working leg back, chest over, do not bounce off the ground. Don’t use the pole to help you get up, it’s just there for stability. 

E. Cable abduction 3x 12-15 
*bring working leg slightly behind non-working leg, slight bend in knee, initiate from glute instead of foot & squeeze hard in top position, go lighter & focus on control rather than momentum.

90 sec rest btw sets. 30 sec rest btw legs if single leg exercise.

Do I have plans on competing? 
No.. ⬇️

This is something I find frustrating about the fitness industry, that just because you go to the gym it’s assumed that the next step is competing, and that you can’t just train out of enjoyment or achieve great physical results without the goal of stepping on stage. 👙

I train because I love it, it makes me feel good, I love pushing myself to see what I’m capable of. I love feeling strong, I love feeling empowered and confident within my skin, knowing the hard work and discipline that has been required to get me to where I am. I love feeling HEALTHY and the relationship I’ve built towards myself. 🙏🏼🤍

Competing is an extreme sport, and not necessarily a healthy one. 
It’s completely glorified and idolised when in reality it’s more common then not to have horrible body body image (even when at their absolute leanest) and eating disorders as a result. 

It is not healthy to get to a ridiculously low body fat percentage, to the point your menstrual cycle stops. 
To be obsessing over food and having to track everything to the exact calorie. 
To train for 3+ hours a day (in a lot of cases it can look more like 5).
The list honestly goes on. 🙄

Competing needs to stop being looked at as this fun activity, because if you don’t do it properly it can be extremely damaging physically but most importantly mentally. You don’t need to compete just because you train, and truthfully, most people shouldn’t be doing it in the first place. It’s not going to fix your negative relationship towards yourself, if anything it will just exaggerate it.

How did the pursuit of getting ‘fit and healthy’ turn into that? You CAN train hard, be consistent, look great and not have to stand on stage and be judged at how well you did.

Up until about 12 months ago I had NO idea you were supposed to ‘look after’ your curls 😅 
The truth is if you even have a slight wave and don’t look after it properly, you probably have more curls than you think! 

This is my personal routine & has really helped enhance my curls and give them more life 🥰 so I hope it helps you too! 🫶🏼

✨I shampoo and condition my hair about 2-3x per week (shampoo the roots only, condition the ends only & leave in for about 5-10 minutes).

✨I gently brush through my hair and get rid of any knots. 

✨After I wash my hair, I lather my hair with leave in conditioner - curly hair naturally is much more dry so it’s important to keep it hydrated. 

✨SCRUNCH CURLS UP! This will help shape your curls.

✨To help enhance and hold the curls I do the 𝘾𝙤𝙩𝙩𝙤𝙣 𝙎𝙝𝙞𝙧𝙩 𝙃𝙖𝙞𝙧 𝙒𝙧𝙖𝙥 and leave it in for 30-60 minutes (this has been a GAME CHANGER for styling my hair especially if going out 🤝🏼) 

✨To lock in the curls I use a gel and scrunch it into my hair. Be careful with some products as some are really thick and heavy, find one that works well with your hair. 

👉🏼Every morning I will wet my hair and scrunch it up as shown to bring my curls back/ style it for the day because you gals knowwww we wake up and there’s nothing cute about it 😂

💇🏽‍♀️I’ve also learnt that you should get a trim roughly every 3 months as curly hair is more prone to split ends. 

🧴I got my products from @thenewlaw @cprhair (not sponsored) but I think it’s so important to find what works best for YOU. I’ve used other peoples recommendations before and it’s RUINED my hair, so be careful 🫶🏼

Here’s 3 tips to help maximise your training:

1. 𝗪𝗔𝗥𝗠 𝗨𝗣 𝗦𝗘𝗧𝗦: Don’t go straight into your working weight, you need to prime the muscle, focus on form under a lighter load and know how the exercise should feel and LOOK before using more challenging weights.
2. 𝗧𝗥𝗨𝗘 𝗪𝗢𝗥𝗞𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗦𝗘𝗧𝗦: Your warm up sets ARE NOT working sets. You need to ensure these sets are challenging and your working close to failure, the last few reps should be HARD but can still maintain good form. You should NOT be able to get more than 5 more reps. **when I refer to failure I mean technique failure. Meaning if you were to keep going you wouldn’t be able to maintain good form, full range of motion, or mind muscle connection. Work within your abilities.**
3. 𝗥𝗘𝗦𝗧: Make sure you’re taking enough rest between sets. REST = BETTER OUTPUT = BETTER RESULTS. But don’t mistake this for too much rest. Set a timer, don’t chat between sets and rest for 90-120 seconds (the bigger the lift, the more rest typically required). We want QUALITY sets, not fatigued sloppy ones.

UPPER BODY 🤝🏼 

I personally love following 2x full upper days instead of muscle splits (eg back & biceps) so that I can hit all the muscle groups 2x instead of just the once. 

I also find because I break it up I’m able to put more into each exercise/ muscle as I’m not working under constant fatigue. 

I love super-setting opposing muscle groups (eg shoulders with back) to reduce rest time, still keep intensity high, yet still allow my muscles to recover so that I can ensure I’m making the most out of my working sets.

I still rest between exercises (60-90 seconds) then by the time I return back I’ve been able to rest that muscle group for a good 2+ minutes so I can push hard again in the next set. 

This is your reminder rest is CRUCIAL for your gains. ✋🏼 this will support you in lifting heavier to support progressive overload (the key to building muscle/ strength).

Eating in a deficit doesn’t mean having tiny boring meals. You just have to be smarter with your nutrition choices and even get a little creative. I truly eat food i love every single day, I make homemade versions of burgers, pizza, pasta, you name it. Small swaps can make a huge difference and eating healthy doesn’t have to be so bland. 🍔🥗🍳

𝗛𝗲𝗿𝗲 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝘀𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗽𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗲𝘀 𝗜 𝗮𝗹𝘄𝗮𝘆𝘀 𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗰𝗸 𝘁𝗼 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗺𝘆 𝗻𝘂𝘁𝗿𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻: 
•base all meals around a protein source. Protein is the most important macronutrient from a body composition stand point. This will support in maintaining and building lean muscle mass + is very satiating which will support in managing hunger levels.
•get in a few serves of veg and fruit each day. These are not only packed with vitamins and minerals that support the body in functioning optimally, but they are also high in fibre which supports gut health aswell as typically lower in calories and very satiating.
•80% wholefoods / 20% soul foods. I don’t cut any food out or label food as ‘good’ or ‘bad’. I ensure majority of my food choices are nutritious, and if I want to enjoy a meal out every now and then, or have some chocolate or ice cream, I allow myself to enjoy it guilt free. It’s not what you do sometimes, it’s what you do most of the time that matters. 
•I always aim to have over 3L water per day. If you struggle with water adding something like diet rite cordial is a great option to give it more flavour.

Stretching is so neglected and underatted, but I can wholeheartedly say will improve your mobility tenfold, which will then transfer into much better training performance AND results. But even further than that, it is so important for overall health and well-being; better posture, less injuries, less pains and aches, more functional, better blood flow, recovery, calming, and a great way to connect with your breath. 

This is my personal routine that I’ve followed for years and LOVE. I like to really breathe into the movements until I feel myself release in it, if an area feels tighter than another I’ll spend more time on it. Flows will be different for everyone, but I find this a great all rounder to help release everywhere from your hips, glutes, back, legs, chest, shoulders, calves, stomach. 
*remember wherever your starting point is OKAY! You may not get anywhere near as deep as I can into the movements, but with time you will improve, and it’s even more reason to stick at it! Be patient and kind with yourself, this is about improvement for you and no one else 🌸

I personally like to do a big flow 1-2x per week, for about 45 minutes. But truly, even getting around to doing 15 minutes 1-2x per week is so much better than none. I promise you, your body will thank you for it. 

We train so hard, and put our bodies through so much stress that we must balance that out with lengthening and releasing that tension. You won’t know how much you need it until you start.

10 years 🫀
Since I was admitted into hospital with AN*. 
The darkness I felt in this time is hard to put into words, I was consumed, miserable and felt hopeless. I no longer wanted to here, I wanted it to be over, to stop living at war with myself every day.

There is so much I could say, but the most overwhelming lesson I’ve learnt is how f’ing wildly capable we are of turning our life around. No matter how lost you are or how dark it gets, you DO hold the power. You are never stuck, never alone, never helpless. 

Our mind is more powerful than we will ever comprehend. 
I learnt first hand how you can train your mind to be your worst enemy. By constantly criticising and bringing yourself down, but you CAN flip that around and train it to become your best friend.
By believing in yourself, cheering yourself on, showing kindness, patience, love, respect. Treat YOURSELF how you would treat someone you loved. 

If you had someone speaking to you the way you speak to yourself, would you keep that person in your life? Probably not, so why would you allow the very person that’s going to be with you FOREVER speak to you the way you do? The quality of your life is determined by the voice inside your head, make sure it’s building you up, not dragging you down. 

You owe it to yourself to make the most out of this one, big, beautiful life. To be happy, to love and accept yourself, to live in a way that feels aligned with who you truly are. We are so strong, so resilient, so smart, and so capable of overcoming AND accomplishing anything. 

I am constantly in awe of how much can change in the matter of a year, let alone 5 years or 10 years. Don’t limit yourself to what is possible, open your mind and trust yourself. You can re-start and change direction at any time. 

Our biggest struggles, often turn into our biggest strengths, and even though it seems impossible to see at the time, one day you can look back and truly appreciate all the lessons it taught you, how it helped shape you into the person you are today & help people in a way you once needed. 

Here’s to a decade of growth, mentally and physically. Don’t ever give up on yourself, you deserve to be here 💛✨

Too many people treat December as if it doesn’t matter, but it does. 
Your routine may not look the exact same, but that’s doesn’t mean you blow it off completely. You can tweak it, make it more realistic for you in this time, simplify it, stick to the basics and be more prepared to make it more manageable. 
Health isn’t just about your physical, it’s for your mental. Looking after yourself shouldn’t be negotiable. 

It’s okay to do less, it’s okay to prioritise other things like socialising, and I encourage that! but that doesn’t mean you have to put yourself and your goals off to the side completely. You deserve more than that, your body deserves more than that, and your mind deserves more than that. 
 
Change up your training if you need to, making it shorter, maybe more fast paced, 3 days instead of 5, doing some classes, walks, yoga, make it more fun and even bring a friend along to hold each other accountable and enjoy it together. 

Instead of nailing your macros, understand events will come up you are allowed and SHOULD enjoy. Be flexible and kind with yourself. Be present in the experiences, 
but still make an effort to base your meals around a lean protein source, always aim to get in some fruit and veg each day, control your meals outside of events and drink lots of water. 

To truly feel your best in this holiday period, you don’t let go of the things that make you feel good. This doesn’t have to be all or nothing, just doing SOMETHING will always leave you feeling better. you’ve worked too hard to get here, don’t toss it to the side now. 🤍🫶🏼
